item.description:
Marco Arment:
 &ldquo;Think of how many people are so afraid of their PCs that they only do the bare minimum with them and never venture into unknown territory because they’re afraid of “breaking” their computers.
How many of them recently bought iPads and have become much more confident and adventurous with usage and applications, since Apple tricked them into thinking that the iPad isn’t a computer?&rdquo;

From the BBC: &ldquo;Patient files &lsquo;more accessible&rsquo;&ldquo;
 The health service is to invest £300m in the next 10 years in information and communication technology.
The investment will mean that anyone in the health service, whether they are in a GP&rsquo;s surgery or a hospital ward, can access a patient&rsquo;s records.
 I sincerely hope that it&rsquo;s NOT going to allow ANYONE in the Health Service to access a patient&rsquo;s records&hellip;

Everything that is wrong and broken with corporate IT, summed up in a single, sad sentence:
 &ldquo;I have nothing against iPhone. It&rsquo;s great,&rdquo; says Manjit Singh, CIO at Chiquita Brands International Inc. &ldquo;But we&rsquo;re a BlackBerry shop, and I don&rsquo;t think iPhone brings anything new to the table. It has a great user experience, but that&rsquo;s all.&rdquo;
 Computerworld: iPhones trickle in the enterprise

If Richard Rogers was a toymaker&hellip;
[![01](http://www.themorningnews.org/images/wild_animals/01.jpg)
&hellip;they&rsquo;d look something like this.

[(http://blip.tv/file/get/Leelefever-RSSInPlainEnglish369.wmv) Click to Play
